[[sn:Tokugōshō]] [[sn:okugōshō]] [[ja:得業生]] [[en:Tokugōshō]]
{{DEFAULTSORT:Tokugōshō}} {{translated page|ja|得業生|version=99494017|comment=Imported full ja history}}

'''Tokugōshō''' (得業生) refers to the status of scholarship students in ancient Japanese educational systems, who were expected to acquire advanced academic knowledge and technical skills beyond those of general [[students]]. It was an upper-level course established in institutions such as {{ill|Daigakuryō|ja|大学寮|1=Daigaku-ryō|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ten'yakuryō|ja|典薬寮|1=Bureau of Pharmacy|2=ja|3=典薬寮|4=fr|5=Bureau de pharmacie|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Overview ==
In {{ill|Tenpyō|ja|天平|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (730), the {{ill|Daijōkan|ja|太政官|1=Daijō-kan|qq=draft|qq=draft}} submitted the following proposal:
Among the students enrolled in the {{ill|Daigakuryō|ja|大学寮|1=Daigaku-ryō|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, some lacked sufficient progress despite their extended study periods, while others, despite their strong academic inclinations, struggled financially to cover their tuition. "We propose selecting students with exceptional talent ({{ill|性識聡慧|ja|せいしきそうけい|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) and superior skills ({{ill|藝業優長|ja|げいぎょうゆうちょう|qq=draft|qq=draft}})—a group of no fewer than five and no more than ten—for dedicated study and providing them with summer and winter clothing as well as rations."
As a result, the Daigakuryō selected {{ill|Meikyōdō|ja|明経道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Confucian studies) students (4), {{ill|Kidendō|ja|紀伝道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (historical studies) students (2), {{ill|Myōhōdō|ja|明法道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (law) students (2), and {{ill|Sandomyō|ja|算道|1=Sandō_(mathematics)|2=ja|3=算道|lt=Sandō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (mathematics) students (2) as ''Tokugōshō''. The same proposal also addressed the aging of various instructors, requiring them to teach their expertise to successors. The proposal instructed {{ill|Yoshinori|ja|吉田宜|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōtsu no Omi|ja|大津首|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tanina no Muraji|ja|谷那庚受|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and others to take disciples in fields such as astronomy, medicine, and calendrical studies, with provisions mirroring those for university students.<ref>''{{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', Tenpyō 2, March 27th entry.</ref>
This initiative led to the establishment of ''Tokugōshō'' specializing in {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} within the Onmyōryō, as well as ''Tokugōshō'' in medicine within the Ten'yakuryō.<ref>''{{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', vol. 16, "Onmyōryō."</ref>
The key distinction lies in the purposes of these programs: ''Tokugōshō'' at the university aimed to promote academic excellence among students, whereas those in the Onmyōryō and Ten'yakuryō were intended for training successors. Both systems were not directly related to the {{ill|Shikibu-shō|ja|式部省|1=Shikibu-shō|lt=Ministry of Ceremonial Affairs|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s formal civil service examinations.
Subsequently, ''Kiden Tokugōshō'' and ''Dazaifu Tokugōshō'' (before {{ill|Jōwa|ja|承和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 12, 845) were established, with graduates undergoing exams to certify their completion and then assuming teaching or specialized governmental positions. Over time, ''Tokugōshō'' became viewed as a preparatory course for the Shikibu-shō's examinations. By {{ill|Engi|ja|延喜|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 13 (913), participation in ''Tokugōshō'' became a prerequisite for examination eligibility, and the system itself evolved into a pathway for becoming a scholar in specialized fields.
Except for {{ill|Bungaku Tokugōshō|ja|文章得業生|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which survived into the early {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, most of these programs disappeared by the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
