As a result, the Daigakuryō selected {{ill|Meikyōdō|ja|明経道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meikyōdō|qq=}} (Confucian studies) students (4), {{ill|Kidendō|ja|紀伝道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kidendō|qq=}} (historical studies) students (2), {{ill|Myōhōdō|ja|明法道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myōhōdō|qq=}} (law) students (2), and {{ill|Sandomyō|ja|算道|1=Sandō_(mathematics)|2=ja|3=算道|lt=Sandō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sandomyō|13=User:Immanuelle/Sandō_(mathematics)|qq=}} (mathematics) students (2) as ''Tokugōshō''. The same proposal also addressed the aging of various instructors, requiring them to teach their expertise to successors. The proposal instructed {{ill|Yoshinori|ja|吉田宜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshinori|qq=}}, {{ill|Ōtsu no Omi|ja|大津首|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtsu no Omi|qq=}}, {{ill|Tanina no Muraji|ja|谷那庚受|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanina no Muraji|qq=}}, and others to take disciples in fields such as astronomy, medicine, and calendrical studies, with provisions mirroring those for university students.<ref>''{{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shoku Nihongi|qq=}}'', Tenpyō 2, March 27th entry.</ref>
This initiative led to the establishment of ''Tokugōshō'' specializing in {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōdō|qq=}}, {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmondō|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmondō (astrology)|qq=}}, and {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rekidō|13=User:Immanuelle/Rekidō|qq=}} within the Onmyōryō, as well as ''Tokugōshō'' in medicine within the Ten'yakuryō.<ref>''{{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki|qq=}}'', vol. 16, "Onmyōryō."</ref>
The key distinction lies in the purposes of these programs: ''Tokugōshō'' at the university aimed to promote academic excellence among students, whereas those in the Onmyōryō and Ten'yakuryō were intended for training successors. Both systems were not directly related to the {{ill|Shikibu-shō|ja|式部省|1=Shikibu-shō|lt=Ministry of Ceremonial Affairs|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikibu-shō|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikibu-shō|qq=}}'s formal civil service examinations.
Subsequently, ''Kiden Tokugōshō'' and ''Dazaifu Tokugōshō'' (before {{ill|Jōwa|ja|承和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōwa|qq=}} 12, 845) were established, with graduates undergoing exams to certify their completion and then assuming teaching or specialized governmental positions. Over time, ''Tokugōshō'' became viewed as a preparatory course for the Shikibu-shō's examinations. By {{ill|Engi|ja|延喜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engi|qq=}} 13 (913), participation in ''Tokugōshō'' became a prerequisite for examination eligibility, and the system itself evolved into a pathway for becoming a scholar in specialized fields.
Except for {{ill|Bungaku Tokugōshō|ja|文章得業生|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bungaku Tokugōshō|qq=}}, which survived into the early {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}, most of these programs disappeared by the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}.
